PART A

DOMAIN:

Telecom

CONTEXT:

A telecom company wants to use their historical customer data to predict behaviour to retain customers. You can analyse all relevant customer data and develop focused customer retention programs.

DATA DESCRIPTION:

Each row represents a customer, each column contains customers attributes described on the column Metadata. The data set includes information about: Customers who left within the last month the column is called Churn Services that each customer has signed up for phone, multiple lines, internet, online security, online backup, device protection, tech support, and streaming TV and movies Customer account information how long theyve been a customer, contract, payment method, paperless billing, monthly charges, and total charges Demographic info about customers gender, age range, and if they have partners and dependents

PROJECT OBJECTIVE:

To Build a model that will help to identify the potential customers who have a higher probability to churn. This helps the company to understand the pinpoints and patterns of customer churn and will increase the focus on strategizing customer retention.

C. Create a function that will accept a DataFrame as input and return pie-charts for all the appropriate Categorical features. Clearly show percentage distribution in the pie-chart. [4 Marks]

Function returning pie charts for categorical features of the dataframe

In[34]:
def plot_pie_chart(df_categorical):
    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 16))
    plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.2, wspace=0.2)
    categorical_features = df_categorical.columns.tolist()
    
    # set number of columns (use 4 to demonstrate the change)
    ncols = 4
    # calculate number of rows
    nrows = len(categorical_features) // ncols + (len(categorical_features) % ncols > 0)

    # loop through the length of tickers and keep track of index
    for n, categorical_feature in enumerate(categorical_features):
        # add a new subplot iteratively using nrows and cols
        ax = plt.subplot(nrows, ncols, n + 1)
        df_categorical[categorical_feature].value_counts().plot(kind='pie', ax=ax, autopct='%1.2f%%')
        ax.set_title(categorical_feature)
        ax.yaxis.set_visible(False)

Remove the customerID as it is not essential column and pass the dataframe to the function to draw pie charts

E. Encode all the appropriate Categorical features with the best suitable approach. [2 Marks]

  • Using label encoding for gender, SeniorCitizen, Partner, Dependents, PhoneService, MultipleLines, OnlineSecurity, OnlineBackup, DeviceProtection, TechSupport, StreamingTV, StreamingMovies, PaperlessBilling, Churn
  • For column PaymentMethod options seems independent and also values cannot be classified as 0 and 1. In the dataset, we can use normalisation for other columns to restrict all values between 0 and 1 to have all columns as equal weightage
  • For columns InternetService and Contract, there is ordinality in the values. Let's dive in more.
    • In Contract, 2 year is the longest and Month-to-month is shortest. As per the correlation matrix, it is less likely for the customer with long term contract to Churn. So, let's do label encoding for Contract
    • Similarly for InternetService, No means customer doesn't have internet service. DSL means the customer has the internet service but it is not fastest and it is older technology. Fiber means customer has the fastest and latest internet technology. So, let's do label encoding for the InternetService
